14 Section 1. Section 46-18-201, MCA, is amended to read:
15 "46-18-201. Sentences that may be imposed. (1) (a) Whenever a person has been found guilty of
16 an offense upon a verdict of guilty or a plea of guilty or nolo contendere, a sentencing judge may defer
17 imposition of sentence, except as otherwise specifically provided by statute, for a period:
18 (i) not exceeding 1 year for a misdemeanor or for a period not exceeding 3 years for a felony; or
19 (ii) not exceeding 2 years for a misdemeanor or for a period not exceeding 6 years for a felony if a
20 financial obligation is imposed as a condition of sentence for either the misdemeanor or the felony, regardless
21 of whether any other conditions are imposed.
22 (b) Except as provided in 46-18-222, imposition of sentence in a felony case may not be deferred
23 in the case of an offender who has been convicted of a felony on a prior occasion, whether or not the sentence
24 was imposed, imposition of the sentence was deferred, or execution of the sentence was suspended.
25 (2) (a) Whenever a person has been found guilty of an offense upon a verdict of guilty or a plea of
26 guilty or nolo contendere, a sentencing judge may suspend execution of sentence, except as provided in
27 subsection (2)(b) or as otherwise specifically provided by statute, for a period up to the maximum sentence
28 allowed or for a period of 6 months, whichever is greater, for each particular offense.
